diagnoses.name: Adult Still's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare type of inflammatory arthritis that features fevers, rash and joint pain. Symptoms might also include a sore throat, pink eye (conjunctivitis), and swollen lymph nodes.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's most commonly seen in children. The symptoms include fever, rash, swelling of the hands and feet, redness in the eyes (conjunctivitis), and lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Acute Rheumatic Fever
diagnoses.description: A disease that can develop from streptococcal infections. It can cause fever, painful and swollen joints, skin rash, and can lead to heart problems.

diagnoses.name: Cellulitis
diagnoses.description: A common bacterial skin infection that causes redness, swelling, and pain in the affected area, potentially accompanied by fever and a general feeling of being unwell.

diagnoses.name: Sepsis
diagnoses.description: A potentially life-threatening condition caused by the body's response to an infection. Sepsis can lead to tissue damage, organ failure, and death. Symptoms include fever, increased heart rate, increased respiratory rate, leukocytosis or leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Dengue Fever
diagnoses.description: A mosquito-borne illness found in tropical and sub-tropical climates worldwide. It can cause high fever, severe headache, pain behind the eyes, joint and muscle pain, rash, and mild bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Chikungunya Virus
diagnoses.description: An infection caused by the Chikungunya virus which leads to sudden onset of fever and severe joint pain. Other symptoms might include headache, muscle pain, joint swelling, or rash.

diagnoses.name: Leptospirosis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial disease that affects humans and animals. Symptoms include high fever, severe headache, chills, muscle aches, and vomiting, which may lead to hand and foot edema.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet Fever
diagnoses.description: An infection that can develop in people who have strep throat. It's characterized by a bright red rash on the body, fever, and sore throat.

diagnoses.name: Erysipelas
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection in the upper layer of the skin. It is similar to another skin condition known as cellulitis, which is an infection in the lower layers. It commonly affects the face and legs and presents with fever, a red, swollen, warm and painful rash, and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki disease
diagnoses.description: Kawasaki disease is a condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It's more frequent in children. The symptoms can include high fever, rash, swelling of hands and feet, redness in the eyes, lips, and throat, along with anemia, leukocytosis, and sometimes pyuria.

diagnoses.name: Scarlet fever
diagnoses.description: Scarlet fever is an infection that can develop in people who have strep throat. It's characterized by a bright red rash on the body, fever, and sore throat, along with the potential for oropharyngeal erythema, leukocytosis, and sometimes anemia.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: SLE is an autoimmune disease in which the immune system attacks its own tissues, causing widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs, including skin rashes, arthritis, and kidney dysfunction, along with anemia, leukocytosis, and occasionally pyuria.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatic fever
diagnoses.description: Rheumatic fever is an inflammatory disease that can develop as a complication of poorly treated strep throat or scarlet fever. Symptoms include fever, painful and tender joints, rash, and oropharyngeal erythema, along with leukocytosis and sometimes anemia.

diagnoses.name: Infectious mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Infectious mononucleosis, often called mono, is a viral infection causing fever, sore throat, and swollen lymph glands, including the spleen. It can also lead to a diffuse erythematous rash, oropharyngeal erythema, leukocytosis, and at times, anemia.

diagnoses.name: Drug reaction with eosinophilia and systemic symptoms (DRESS) syndrome
diagnoses.description: DRESS syndrome is a severe reaction to certain drugs characterized by skin rash, fever, lymph node enlargement, and involvement of internal organs, potential hematological abnormalities like leukocytosis, anemia, and pyuria.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Shock Syndrome (TSS)
diagnoses.description: TSS is a rare, life-threatening complication of certain bacterial infections. It's commonly associated with certain types of tampon use, but it can also occur with skin infections. Symptoms include high fever, rash, low blood pressure, and multi-organ dysfunction, with possible leukocytosis and anemia.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein purpura
diagnoses.description: Henoch-Schönlein purpura is an inflammation of the small blood vessels that causes the vessels in the skin, intestines, kidneys, and joints to bleed, leading to a rash, joint pain, abdominal pain, and kidney involvement, with potential for anemia and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson syndrome/toxic epidermal necrolysis (SJS/TEN)
diagnoses.description: SJS/TEN is a rare, serious disorder of your skin and mucous membranes. It's usually a reaction to medication or an infection. Symptoms include flu-like symptoms, followed by a painful red or purplish rash that spreads and blisters, eventually causing the top layer of your skin to die and shed, often accompanied by leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Acute HIV infection
diagnoses.description: Acute HIV infection is the initial stage of HIV and lasts until the body has created antibodies against the virus. Symptoms can mimic those of the flu, including fever, sore throat, and rash, along with leukocytosis and sometimes anemia.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect multiple systems including the kidneys, joints, skin, heart, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints but can also cause systemic issues such as fever and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder in children causing joint inflammation, and it can also lead to pericardial effusion and fever.

diagnoses.name: Infectious (Septic) Arthritis
diagnoses.description: Infection in a joint causing inflammation (synovitis), often accompanied by fever. Could also be part of a more systemic infection affecting other organs.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease characterized by hardening of the skin, and can also affect internal organs, including the kidneys and heart (pericardial effusion).

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that may present features of three other diseases — lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis — including synovitis, nephritis, and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that causes inflammation of small and medium-sized arteries, potentially leading to symptoms in various organs, including kidneys and heart.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by Borrelia bacteria, transmitted by ticks. It can cause arthritis, myocarditis, and sometimes nephritis if left untreated.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infections
diagnoses.description: Certain viruses can cause a syndrome involving fever, joint pain (arthropathy), and sometimes involvement of the kidneys and heart.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can affect multiple organs in the body, including lungs, joints, and skin, and sometimes the kidneys and heart.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with symptoms such as malar rash (butterfly rash), arthralgia or arthropathy, leukopenia, and less commonly, delirium (neuropsychiatric lupus). Synovitis is also a potential manifestation, related to lupus arthritis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: While primarily known for causing joint pain and arthropathy, RA can occasionally lead to systemic symptoms such as leukopenia (Felty's syndrome) and synovitis, characteristic of the disease's involvement of synovial joints. Delirium is less commonly associated but can occur in severe, systemic cases.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: This condition shares features with systemic lupus erythematosus, systemic sclerosis, and polymyositis, including arthropathy, synovitis, leukopenia, and rashes. Neurological symptoms including mood disorders or cognitive dysfunction, which could progress to severe neuropsychiatric manifestations like delirium, may also be present.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily affects exocrine glands leading to dry eyes and mouth, but can have systemic manifestations including arthropathy, leukopenia, and skin rashes. Neurological involvement is less common but can include a variety of symptoms, potentially including delirium.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: This inflammation of the blood vessels can cause a wide range of symptoms depending on the specific type and organs involved. Symptoms can include skin rashes (potentially resembling a malar rash), joint pain (arthropathy), and in severe cases, organ involvement leading to leukopenia or neuropsychiatric symptoms such as delirium.

diagnoses.name: Drug-induced Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.rationale: Certain medications can induce a lupus-like syndrome presenting with features similar to SLE, including malar rash, arthropathy, leukopenia, and neurological symptoms. Synovitis can also occur in this context. Symptoms often improve upon discontinuation of the offending drug.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.rationale: Caused by the Epstein-Barr virus, it can lead to symptoms such as a rash that could be confused with a malar rash, leukopenia, and delirium, especially in severe or atypical cases. Joint pain or arthropathy can also present in some patients.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: This inflammatory condition involves muscle weakness and distinctive skin rashes, which can sometimes resemble a malar rash. Though primarily affecting the skin and muscles, dermatomyositis can associate with arthropathy, and in severe cases, leukopenia or neuropsychiatric symptoms could be present.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.rationale: An infectious disease caused by Borrelia burgdorferi, transmitted by ticks. It can cause a wide range of symptoms, including arthropathy (Lyme arthritis), skin rash, and potentially neurologic symptoms such as delirium in the later stages (neuroborreliosis). Leukopenia is less common but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body. It can lead to symptoms including arthritis, skin rashes which might be confused with a malar rash in some cases, and less commonly, leukopenia or neurological manifestations (including confusion or delirium).

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease characterized by systemic inflammation affecting multiple organs including the kidneys (nephritis), skin (follicular hyperkeratosis), and possibly leading to serious complications such as pericardial effusion, pleural effusion, and autoimmune hemolysis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: While primarily affecting joints, this systemic autoimmune disease can also cause pleural effusion, pericardial effusion, and other systemic manifestations like rheumatoid vasculitis that might indirectly lead to conditions such as nephritis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that may present features of various connective tissue diseases including lupus, polymyositis, and scleroderma. MCTD can cause a wide range of symptoms such as nephritis, pleural effusion, and pericardial effusion.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease primarily affecting the exocrine glands but can also present systemic involvement such as nephritis and potentially pleural effusion through associated immune complex mediated mechanisms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder characterized by skin thickening and hardening (which could involve follicular hyperkeratosis), but it also affects internal organs and can lead to pleural effusion, pericardial effusion, and kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and skin rash. While primarily affecting skin and muscles, it can have systemic effects including pericardial effusion and, in chronic cases, might contribute to lung and kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa
diagnoses.description: A serious blood vessel disease causing the vessels to become swollen and damaged. While its direct symptoms may not always align perfectly, its systemic nature can lead to complications such as nephritis and in severe cases, effusions.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder in which the immune system destroys the body's red blood cells, white blood cells, and/or platelets. It directly involves autoimmune hemolysis and could be associated with other autoimmune conditions that cause the remaining symptoms.

diagnoses.name: IgG4-related disease
diagnoses.description: A fibroinflammatory condition marked by a tendency to form tumefactive lesions that can affect any organ. It has been associated with pericardial and pleural effusions and can have renal manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Not an autoimmune disease but a type of blood cancer that can present with symptoms similar to those seen in autoimmune diseases, such as pericardial effusion, pleural effusion, nephritis, and indirectly lead to autoimmune hemolysis through autoantibodies.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the force of the blood against the artery walls is too high. Often has no symptoms, but it can lead to serious problems such as heart disease and stroke. Hypertension can cause epistaxis due to the increased pressure on the delicate vessels in the nose. The disease might also indirectly affect vision focusing ability due to its potential impact on the eye's blood vessels. Hypertension is a risk factor for atherosclerosis, where arteries narrow and harden due to the build-up of plaque.

diagnoses.name: Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.description: A neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by an ongoing pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development. Individuals with ADHD might experience difficulty focusing vision as part of their inattention symptoms. Hyperactivity is one of the core symptoms of the disorder.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that affect how your body uses blood sugar (glucose). High blood sugar levels can lead to severe problems with your heart, nerves, eyes, kidneys, and blood vessels. Diabetes can contribute to atherosclerosis and periodontal disease. Although not directly linked, uncontrolled diabetes can affect the body's healing process, potentially exacerbating conditions like epistaxis through fragile blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin Deficiency (Vitamin C and K)
diagnoses.description: Deficiency in Vitamin C can lead to weakened blood vessels, making one more susceptible to epistaxis and periodontal disease due to its role in collagen formation and wound healing. Vitamin K is essential for blood clotting, and its deficiency might also contribute to easier bruising and bleeding.

diagnoses.name: Liver Disease
diagnoses.description: Liver conditions can affect coagulation and the body's ability to manage toxins and hormones, which may lead to atherosclerosis, epistaxis due to impaired blood clotting, and periodontal disease indirectly through overall decreased health. Liver disease can also impact the body's ability to process and store vitamins necessary for visual health and blood vessel integrity.

diagnoses.name: Obstructive Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by breathing repeatedly starting and stopping during sleep. It has been associated with hypertension and consequently with atherosclerosis. The disruption in sleep may contribute to symptoms of hyperactivity and difficulty focusing during the day.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: Chronic kidney disease causes a gradual loss of kidney function over time. It can lead to hypertension and is closely linked with the development of atherosclerosis. The accumulation of toxins can also affect mental clarity and the body's overall health, potentially worsening symptoms of hyperactivity and focus.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune condition that causes inflammation in the joints but can also affect other tissues, including those in the vascular system, increasing the risk for atherosclerosis. Periodontal disease is more common in people with rheumatoid arthritis due to the inflammation affecting various tissues.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders (Hyperthyroidism)
diagnoses.description: Hyperthyroidism can increase metabolism and cause symptoms of hyperactivity. It may also indirectly contribute to ocular symptoms and cardiovascular issues like hypertension, which can exacerbate conditions such as atherosclerosis.

diagnoses.name: Substance Abuse (Cocaine, Amphetamines)
diagnoses.description: Abuse of substances such as cocaine and amphetamines can lead to hyperactivity, hypertension, and epistaxis due to their effects on the cardiovascular system and nasal mucosa. The toxic effects can contribute to atherosclerosis and overall poor health, including oral health.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition where the kidneys don't work as well as they should. It's associated with various systemic implications, such as cardiovascular disease.

diagnoses.name: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder
diagnoses.description: A mental disorder where people feel the need to check things repeatedly, perform certain routines repeatedly, or have certain thoughts repeatedly.

diagnoses.name: Takotsubo Cardiomyopathy
diagnoses.description: Also known as stress cardiomyopathy, it is a transient heart condition often precipitated by episodes of severe emotional or physical stress.

diagnoses.name: Generalized Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by excessive, uncontrollable and often irrational worry about everyday things that is disproportionate to the actual source of worry.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of your body. It's characterized by periods of illness, called flares, and periods of wellness, or remission.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including those in the hands and feet. In some people, the condition can damage a wide variety of body systems, including the skin, eyes, lungs, heart, and blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal increase of white blood cells.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder that causes inflammation of the blood vessels in your nose, sinuses, throat, lungs, and kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth. The disorder can also affect other parts of the body, including the kidneys and blood vessels.

diagnoses.name: Nasal Polyps
diagnoses.description: Soft, painless, noncancerous growths on the lining of your nasal passages or sinuses. They result from chronic inflammation due to asthma, recurring infection, allergies, drug sensitivity, or certain immune disorders.

diagnoses.name: Dehydration
diagnoses.reasoning: Dehydration can contribute to headache, xerosis, and potentially exacerbate hemorrhoids due to concentrated bowel movements.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Iron deficiency anemia may lead to headache and, in severe cases, might relate to dysgeusia. It could indirectly affect hemorrhoids by influencing bowel movement consistency.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Diabetes could cause xerosis and contribute to headache through glucose imbalances. It's also associated with a higher risk of developing hemorrhoids.

diagnoses.name: Benign Essential Blepharospasm
diagnoses.reasoning: Directly accounts for the blepharospasm symptom.

diagnoses.name: Bell's Palsy
diagnoses.reasoning: Bell's Palsy can cause facial muscle weakness or paralysis that might manifest as blepharospasm, and potentially affect taste (dysgeusia).

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.reasoning: Multiple sclerosis can cause a wide array of neurological symptoms including dysgeusia and blepharospasm. Headache is not a common symptom, but it can occur.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause both xerosis and, to some extent, contribute to the development of hemorrhoids due to constipation. It might also cause headaches.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Can lead to xerosis and cause dysgeusia due to the buildup of toxins in the blood. It might also be linked to headaches due to high blood pressure.

diagnoses.name: Parkinson's Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Parkinson's disease might present with blepharospasm as part of its spectrum of movement disorders, and dysgeusia due to involvement of the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Gastrointestinal Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain gastrointestinal disorders, such as inflammatory bowel disease, can cause hemorrhoids, and indirectly lead to headache and xerosis through systemic effects like dehydration.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Back Pain
diagnoses.description: A pain in the back that persists for 12 weeks or longer, even after an initial injury or underlying cause of acute back pain has been treated.

diagnoses.name: Eosinophilia
diagnoses.description: A higher than normal level of eosinophils in the blood, which may indicate a parasitic infection, allergic reaction, or cancer.

diagnoses.name: Cutaneous Angiomata
diagnoses.description: Benign tumors that are made up of small blood vessels. They can occur anywhere on the body.

diagnoses.name: Sinusitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation or swelling of the tissue lining the sinuses. It can be acute or chronic.

diagnoses.name: Churg-Strauss Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A disorder marked by blood vessel inflammation. It can lead to eosinophilia and can affect various organs, including the lungs and the skin, potentially causing angiomata.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A blood disorder characterized by a high number of eosinophils. It may affect multiple organs, including the heart, lungs, skin, and nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Interstitial Cystitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition causing bladder pressure, bladder pain and sometimes pelvic pain, mimicking a urinary tract infection but with no infection present.

diagnoses.name: Ankylosing Spondylitis
diagnoses.description: A form of arthritis that primarily affects the spine, causing severe, chronic pain and discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and pain in any part of the body. It sometimes leads to kidney issues that can present symptoms similar to a UTI.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which your thyroid gland doesn't produce enough of certain crucial hormones, potentially causing issues like osteopenia, attention deficit, and goiter.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder caused by prolonged exposure to high levels of cortisol. It can result in osteopenia, increased glucose levels leading to glycemic lability, and attention deficits.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease in which the immune system eats away at the protective covering of nerves. It can present with symptoms like pseudoseizures due to its impact on the nervous system.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues. It can sometimes present with headache and attention deficit.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms, focused around a severe and debilitating headache. Symptoms can include nausea, light sensitivity, and more.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A group of diseases that result in too much sugar in the blood (high blood glucose). Can be linked to glycemic lability and, in long term, contribute to osteopenia.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A central nervous system disorder in which brain activity becomes abnormal, causing seizures or periods of unusual behavior, sensations, and sometimes loss of awareness.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.description: A mood disorder that causes a persistent feeling of sadness and loss of interest. Can lead to a wide array of psychological and physical symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Primary Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.description: An endocrine disorder caused by overactive parathyroid glands, resulting in high levels of parathyroid hormone. This condition can cause osteopenia and kidney stones.

diagnoses.name: Non-Epileptic Attack Disorder (NEAD)
diagnoses.description: Also known as pseudoseizures, NEAD is a condition where individuals have seizure-like attacks without any electrical disruptions in the brain.

diagnoses.name: Endometriosis
diagnoses.description: A painful disorder in which tissue similar to the lining inside the uterus grows outside the uterus, causing severe dysmenorrhea and can lead to other symptoms including pain during intercourse, pain with bowel movements or urination, and infertility.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. Women with PCOS may have infrequent or prolonged menstrual periods or excess male hormone (androgen) levels. The ovaries may develop numerous small collections of fluid (follicles) and fail to regularly release eggs, leading to dysmenorrhea.

diagnoses.name: Hypersensitivity Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of blood vessels due to an allergic reaction, which can lead to skin lesions, joint pain, and in some cases, abdominal pain or kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Extrinsic (Allergic) Asthma
diagnoses.description: Triggered by exposure to allergens, this type of asthma is associated with eosinophilia and hypersensitivity reactions, and can exacerbate symptoms like hyperactivity due to difficulty breathing.

diagnoses.description: Stress-related and Somatoform Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Pseudoseizures, often found in Conversion Disorder, correlate with psychological distress, which can also manifest as depression and obsessive-compulsive behavior.

diagnoses.description: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease that can cause Lymphadenopathy, leukocytosis, and neuropsychiatric manifestations including depression and anxiety-related behaviors.

diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Infection
diagnoses.reasoning: HIV can cause generalized Lymphadenopathy, leukocytosis as a response to infection, and has been associated with a range of neuropsychiatric conditions, including depression.

diagnoses.description: Lymphoma
diagnoses.reasoning: Lymphoma can present with Lymphadenopathy and leukocytosis. Depression and OCD behaviors can occur as a response to the stress of having a chronic condition.

diagnoses.description: Major Depressive Disorder with Psychotic Features
diagnoses.reasoning: Severe depression can present with somatic symptoms and may also influence the development of obsessive-compulsive behaviors. Immune response alterations in depression can sometimes manifest as leukocytosis.

diagnoses.description: Thyroid Disorders (e.g., Hyperthyroidism, Hypothyroidism)
diagnoses.reasoning: Thyroid dysfunctions can cause depressive symptoms, influence immune function (potentially affecting white blood cell count), and may be linked with anxiety and obsessive behaviors.

diagnoses.description: Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder (OCD)
diagnoses.reasoning: Primary diagnosis when considering depressive episodes and obsessive-compulsive behavior, though it directly doesn't cause Lymphadenopathy or leukocytosis, somatic symptoms might appear in severe cases.

diagnoses.description: Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder (PTSD)
diagnoses.reasoning: PTSD can manifest with depressive symptoms, obsessive thoughts, and somatic symptoms such as pseudoseizures, due to the stress and anxiety from traumatic events.

diagnoses.description: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.reasoning: MS can have neurological symptoms that mimic pseudoseizures, and it's associated with depression. Immune dysregulation in MS could also theoretically contribute to leukocytosis and Lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.description: Autoimmune Disorders with Psychiatric Manifestations
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain autoimmune disorders can cause both physical and psychiatric symptoms, including leukocytosis, Lymphadenopathy, depression, and anxiety-related behaviors.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests
diagnoses: Connective Tissue Disease (e.g., Sjögren’s syndrome with kidney involvement)
Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS Syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD)
diagnoses.rationale: ADHD is diagnosed based on a pattern of inattention, hyperactivity, and impulsivity that interferes with functioning or development. Attention deficit is a core symptom.

diagnoses.name: Chronic otitis externa
diagnoses.rationale: Otitis externa is an inflammation of the outer ear and ear canal. Chronic cases can indicate an ongoing condition or an issue that recurs due to unresolved underlying factors.

diagnoses.name: Viral laryngitis
diagnoses.rationale: Laryngitis, particularly from viral infections, is common and could co-occur with other symptoms due to a general immune response or systemic illness.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.rationale: PCOS can cause infertility due to hormonal imbalances affecting ovulation. While not directly related to other listed symptoms, it's a common cause of infertility.

diagnoses.name: Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS)
diagnoses.rationale: IBS can cause migratory abdominal pain due to its nature as a functional gastrointestinal disorder. Stress and physical health issues can exacerbate IBS symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Endometriosis
diagnoses.rationale: Endometriosis can cause infertility and is often characterized by abdominal pain, though it doesn't commonly cause laryngitis or otitis externa.

diagnoses.name: Gastroenteritis
diagnoses.rationale: Gastroenteritis can cause abdominal pain and might co-occur with ear and throat infections due to a generalized immune response. It doesn't typically cause infertility.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Stress or Anxiety
diagnoses.rationale: Chronic stress can lead to or exacerbate attention deficit symptoms and contribute to somatic symptoms like gastrointestinal upset. It can also impact fertility indirectly.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.rationale: Thyroid disorders can lead to a range of symptoms including attentional deficits, infertility, and potential metabolic disturbances affecting general health.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Celiac disease is an autoimmune disorder that can cause a range of symptoms, including abdominal pain and fertility issues, due to malabsorption of nutrients.

diagnoses: Hashimoto's Thyroiditis leading to transient hyperthyroidism
Thyroid Nodule producing excess thyroid hormone

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (Crohn's Disease and Ulcerative Colitis)

diagnoses.name: Job Syndrome (Hyper-IgE Syndrome)
diagnoses.description: A rare immunodeficiency disorder characterized by high levels of serum IgE, eczema, and recurrent skin and lung infections. Patients may exhibit features like dermatographism and have an increased risk of autoimmune manifestations which could possibly relate to symptoms like irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by the development of hives and dermatographism, which is a hive-like reaction upon physical scratching or rubbing of the skin. It might also involve immune system components, including altered immunoglobulins and occasional eye irritations due to associated allergies.

diagnoses.name: Common Variable Immunodeficiency
diagnoses.description: An immune disorder characterized by a reduction in immunoglobulins, leading to an increased susceptibility to infections. Individuals with this condition might also experience autoimmune phenomena that can include skin and mucosal symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Selective IgA Deficiency
diagnoses.description: The most common primary immunodeficiency, characterized by an isolated decrease in serum IgA. It can be associated with allergic reactions and autoimmune conditions, potentially relating to dermatographism and ocular irritation.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren’s Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder primarily characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth but can also involve a reduction in certain immunoglobulins and can be associated with other autoimmune skin manifestations.

diagnoses.name: Atopic Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition marked by inflamed, itchy skin which can also lead to dermatographism in some cases. People with atopic dermatitis can have elevated IgE levels and sometimes experience issues with ocular irritation due to associated allergic conjunctivitis.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Thrombocytopenic Purpura
diagnoses.description: An immune disorder characterized by the immune system attacking its platelets, leading to easy bruising and bleeding. It's associated with autoimmune disorders and can present alterations in immunoglobulin levels. Though not directly related to the specified symptoms, the autoimmune nature can have overlapping presentations.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A systemic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, including skin (dermatographism), eyes (irritation), and the immune system (altered immunoglobulin levels). Patients can have obsessive-compulsive behaviors related to their disease management.

diagnoses.name: Psychiatric Disorders
diagnoses.description: This includes a spectrum of disorders where obsessive-compulsive behaviors present as primary or secondary symptoms. For patients with a primary immunodeficiency or systemic disease, psychological manifestations can be a significant part of their condition.

diagnoses.name: Autism Spectrum Disorder
diagnoses.description: While not directly associated with the immunological or dermatographic symptoms, individuals with autism may exhibit obsessive-compulsive behaviors and have an increased incidence of immune dysfunctions. Co-occurring conditions might account for the dermatological and eye symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often presents with dry eyes and mouth, which can cause oral pain and eye irritation. It might indirectly lead to fibrotic changes.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to oral ulcers (causing oral pain), eye irritation, and possibly other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes that's usually a reaction to a medication or an infection. Symptoms may include pain in the mucous membranes and eye irritation.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease in which the body's immune system mistakenly attacks healthy tissue. It can cause leukocytosis, oral pain through ulcers, and fibrosis in severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that can cause fibrosis of the lung and dry eyes (Sjögren's syndrome), and is associated with systemic symptoms like leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Chemical Exposure
diagnoses.description: Exposure to certain chemicals can cause eye irritation, leukocytosis, oral pain, and in severe or prolonged cases, fibrosis of the lungs or other organs.

diagnoses.name: Graft vs Host Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when donor bone marrow or stem cells attack the recipient. Can cause dry eyes, oral pain, leukocytosis, and fibrosis.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: Though primarily associated with fatigue and pallor, severe cases can lead to dry eyes and oral pain due to mucosal changes.

diagnoses.name: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: A chronic inflammatory condition of the mouth that can cause painful oral lesions and may be associated with eye irritation.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: A type of inflammatory bowel disease that can lead to mouth ulcers (causing oral pain), eye irritation, and in the long term, fibrosis in various parts of the body.

diagnoses: Immune Dysregulation, Polyendocrinopathy, Enteropathy, X-linked Syndrome (IPEX Syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Carcinoid Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A syndrome that results from a carcinoid tumor which secretes serotonin and other chemicals that can cause flushing, diarrhea, and difficulty breathing.
diagnoses.relevance: Flushing is a hallmark symptom of carcinoid syndrome, which may also impact cardiac and pulmonary systems, potentially influencing sleep apnea indirectly.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues supporting the skin, bones, blood vessels, and many other organs and tissues, characterized by hypermobility.
diagnoses.relevance: Hypermobility is characteristic of Ehlers-Danlos, which can also have vascular implications that might indirectly affect flushing and lymphadenitis.

diagnoses.name: Mast Cell Activation Syndrome (MCAS)
diagnoses.description: A condition in which mast cells release too much of certain substances in response to triggers, leading to symptoms like flushing, lightheadedness, and skin lesions.
diagnoses.relevance: MCAS can cause flushing and contribute to lymphadenitis due to immune dysregulation.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that begins in infection-fighting cells of the immune system, called lymphocytes, often leading to lymphadenitis, fever, and weight loss.
diagnoses.relevance: Lymphadenitis is a primary symptom of lymphoma, with other systemic effects potentially contributing to obstructive sleep apnea and difficulty focusing vision.

diagnoses.name: Phaeochromocytoma
diagnoses.description: A rare, usually benign tumor that develops in the adrenal gland and can cause high blood pressure, heart palpitations, flushing, and headaches.
diagnoses.relevance: Flushing is a symptom of phaeochromocytoma, with the condition’s effect on blood pressure potentially exacerbating sleep apnea symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Marfan Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An inherited disorder that affects connective tissue — the fibers that support and anchor your organs and other structures in your body, known for causing tall stature, long extremities, and hypermobility.
diagnoses.relevance: While not directly causing flushing or lymphadenitis, Marfan syndrome's connective tissue effects and cardiovascular implications could indirectly influence these symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that affects multiple organs in the body, but mostly the lungs and lymph glands. Symptoms include tiredness, swollen lymph nodes, and a red rash on the face or hands.
diagnoses.relevance: Sarcoidosis can lead to lymphadenitis and, through systemic inflammation, might contribute to sleep apnea and vascular issues inducing flushing.

diagnoses.name: Rosacea
diagnoses.description: A chronic, inflammatory skin condition that most often affects the face. Rosacea worsens with time if left untreated and is often characterized by redness, pimples, and visible blood vessels.
diagnoses.relevance: Rosacea directly causes flushing and can be comorbid with ocular issues, possibly affecting vision focus.

diagnoses.name: Sleep Apnea, Obstructive
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which breathing repeatedly stops and starts during sleep due to throat muscles intermittently relaxing and blocking the airway.
diagnoses.relevance: A primary condition that matches one of the symptoms directly.

diagnoses.name: Hyperthyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland is overactive and produces an excessive amount of thyroid hormones. Symptoms may include weight loss, nervousness, and difficulty focusing.
diagnoses.relevance: Hyperthyroidism can cause flushing and, by affecting metabolic rate, might contribute to sleep disturbances, including sleep apnea.

diagnoses: Thyroid Disorders (such as Graves' Disease or Hashimoto's Thyroiditis)

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by dry eyes and mouth, which can lead to increased immunoglobulins and anxiety due to chronic discomfort.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause a wide range of symptoms, including skin manifestations like xerosis, increased immunoglobulins, and possibly angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Hypereosinophilic Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by an elevated eosinophil count, which can cause a variety of symptoms including angioedema, xerosis, and irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Idiopathic Urticaria
diagnoses.description: A condition of unknown cause that produces hives; it can be associated with angioedema and often results in anxiety due to its unpredictable flare-ups.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder leading to recurrent attacks of severe swelling (angioedema), which can be accompanied by skin conditions such as xerosis.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-Host Disease (GvHD)
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs after an allogeneic tissue transplant, which can cause skin dryness (xerosis), irritated eyes, and elevated immunoglobulin levels.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders where part of the body's immune system is missing or does not function properly, leading to increased infections, which can cause symptoms like xerosis, angioedema, and anxiety.

diagnoses.name: Allergic Contact Dermatitis
diagnoses.description: An allergic reaction to a substance that comes in contact with the skin, which can cause symptoms like xerosis and irritated eyes.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorder
diagnoses.description: A mental health disorder characterized by feelings of worry, anxiety, or fear that are strong enough to interfere with one's daily activities. While primarily a psychiatric condition, it can also exacerbate or contribute to the perception of physical symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease known for its distinctive skin rash, muscle weakness, and systemic features, including increased risk of malignancy. Symptoms can include skin dryness and irritation of the eyes.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immune Deficiency Disorders
diagnoses.description: These disorders make the body more susceptible to infections due to an intrinsic defect in the immune system. Sinusitis and increased susceptibility to infections can be common in patients, and some conditions may impact fertility.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect any part of the body, including the joints, skin, and organs. SLE can cause a wide range of symptoms, including increased susceptibility to infections and potentially leading to issues like vaginitis due to its effects on the immune system.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition. CFS may present with symptoms such as postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome (POTS) and increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that causes chronic inflammation of the joints and can also affect other organs. The chronic inflammation might lead to increased susceptibility to infections, and autoimmune effects can sometimes lead to secondary infertility.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands responsible for keeping the eyes, mouth, and other parts of the body moist. It is associated with increased susceptibility to infections, and systemic effects can indirectly influence fertility.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: A metabolic disorder characterized by high blood sugar levels over a prolonged period. Poorly controlled diabetes can lead to increased susceptibility to infections and complications that may affect fertility.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) is a virus that attacks the body's immune system. If not treated, it can lead to the disease AIDS (Acquired Immunodeficiency Syndrome). Sinusitis and increased susceptibility to infections are common in individuals with HIV/AIDS.

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.description: A hormonal disorder common among women of reproductive age. Women with PCOS may experience infrequent or prolonged menstrual periods or excess male hormone (androgen) levels. PCOS is a common cause of infertility.

diagnoses.name: Thyroid Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions that affect the thyroid gland, which regulates metabolism, energy generation, and mood. Thyroid disorders can lead to a range of symptoms, including infertility and possibly increased susceptibility to infections.

diagnoses.name: Endometriosis
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which tissue similar to the lining inside the uterus (the endometrium) grows outside the uterus. Endometriosis can cause significant pain and infertility.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by recurrent attacks of moderate to severe pain. The aura may manifest as scintillation and can be followed by dysphagia in some cases.

diagnoses.name: Transient ischemic attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA may cause symptoms like scintillation and temporary difficulty swallowing or dysphagia.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A cerebrovascular accident causing brain damage can manifest as headache, visual disturbances (scintillation), and dysphagia due to muscle control loss.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: Depending on its location, a brain tumor can cause headaches, scintillation, or visual disturbances and dysphagia.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition affecting the central nervous system, leading to symptoms like dysphagia and, less commonly, scintillation or visual disturbances as part of an optic neuritis, in addition to headaches.

diagnoses.name: Esophageal stricture
diagnoses.description: A narrowing of the esophagus that causes dysphagia. While not directly related, patients might also experience headaches and, in rare cases, visual symptoms due to associated conditions.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia gravis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease characterized by weakness in the voluntary muscles, leading to dysphagia and potentially contributing to headache and visual disturbances like scintillation due to weakness in ocular muscles.

diagnoses.name: Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD)
diagnoses.description: While primarily known for acid reflux and heartburn, severe cases can cause dysphagia. Associated discomfort can lead to headaches, but scintillation is unlikely directly related.

diagnoses.name: Benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV)
diagnoses.description: A condition that could cause headaches and, potentially, visual disturbances like scintillation. Dysphagia is not a common symptom but could be related indirectly via severe nausea.

diagnoses.name: Achillasia
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder making it difficult for food and liquid to pass into the stomach, causing dysphagia. Headaches and scintillation are not directly related but could stem from the stress or malnutrition associated with the condition.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of your brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Strokes may cause symptoms such as paralysis, speech difficulties, and numbness or weakness in the face, arm, or leg, especially on one side of the body.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: A transient ischemic attack (TIA) is often called a mini-stroke. It's similar to a stroke but lasts only a few minutes and causes no permanent damage. It may manifest as temporary paralysis, numbness, or aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers and causes communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms may include numbness, weakness, and in more severe cases, aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: Peripheral neuropathy results from damage to the peripheral nerves and causes weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in your hands and feet. It can also affect other areas and body functions, including digestion and urination.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Brain tumors can cause a variety of symptoms based on their location and size. Some may experience numbness or tingling in parts of the body, difficulties with speech (aphasia), or other neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: Guillain-Barre syndrome is a rare disorder in which your body's immune system attacks your nerves. The first symptoms are typically weakness and tingling in your extremities. These sensations can quickly spread, eventually paralyzing your whole body.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: Complex migraines can mimic strokes and may cause temporary paralysis (hemiplegia), speech disturbances, and tingling or numbness of the face or extremities. Unlike strokes, these symptoms are typically reversible and last from a few hours to a few days.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes
diagnoses.description: Diabetes can lead to diabetic neuropathy, a type of nerve damage due to high blood sugar levels. Symptoms can include numbness, tingling, or pain in the hands, feet, and other parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: Lyme disease is transmitted by the bite of an infected tick. Early symptoms may include a rash and flu-like symptoms. Neurological complications, including paralysis and aphasia, can appear if the infection is not treated.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: ALS, also known as Lou Gehrig’s disease, is a progressive neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord. Early symptoms can include muscle weakness or stiffness. Progression can lead to speech difficulties (including aphasia) and numbness.

diagnoses: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS, also known as Lou Gehrig's Disease)

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.details: Migraine headaches can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine attacks can go through four stages: prodrome, aura, attack, and post-drome.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.details: Acoustic neuroma is a benign tumor that develops on the nerve that connects the ear to the brain. The tumor usually grows slowly and can cause hearing loss, ringing in your ear (tinnitus), and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.details: Multiple Sclerosis (MS) is a chronic autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It can cause weakness, tingling, lack of coordination, and problems with vision, balance, and muscle control.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.details: Meniere's Disease affects the inner ear and causes episodes of vertigo (spinning sensation), hearing loss, tinnitus (ringing in the ear), and sometimes a feeling of fullness or pressure in your ear.

diagnoses.name: Viral Infection
diagnoses.details: Certain viral infections can cause symptoms like headache, weakness, and hearing loss, either through direct effects or through complications such as meningitis.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.details: Anemia, particularly iron-deficiency anemia, can lead to symptoms such as weakness, dizziness, and headaches due to insufficient oxygen delivery to tissues and organs.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.details: Brain tumors, whether benign or malignant, can increase pressure in the brain, leading to symptoms such as headaches, hearing loss, and weakness or numbness in parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.details: Lyme disease is an infectious disease caused by Borrelia bacteria, transmitted to humans through the bite of infected black-legged ticks. Symptoms can include headache, fatigue, and possible neurological deficits, including hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.details: Hypothyroidism, or low thyroid function, can lead to symptoms such as fatigue, weight gain, depression, and can also be associated with hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Ototoxic Medication Reaction
diagnoses.details: Certain medications are known to be ototoxic, meaning they can cause hearing damage as well as balance disorders. Symptoms can include hearing loss, tinnitus, and sometimes headaches and weakness, particularly if the medication affects other systems as well.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of headache characterized by severe head pain followed or accompanied by sensory disturbances such as flashes of light, blind spots, tingling in the arms and legs, nausea, vomiting, and increased sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Migraine without Aura
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms including headache, nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound. Unlike migraines with aura, these do not include visual or sensory disturbances before the headache begins.

diagnoses.name: Tension-type Headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by a constant pressure or ache around the head, especially at the temples or back of the head and neck. Not typically accompanied by other sensory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Cluster Headache
diagnoses.description: A condition that produces severe headaches on one side of the head. It is called 'cluster headache' because the attacks come in groups, often with one or more episodes occurring daily over a period of weeks or months.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA is characterized by temporary stroke-like symptoms, including paralysis, speech difficulties, and mental confusion, which often resolve within 24 hours.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the central nervous system that can cause numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision, and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain, which can be cancerous (malignant) or non-cancerous (benign). Headache and neurological deficits like parasthesia may occur depending on the tumor’s location and size.

diagnoses.name: Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from damage to the peripheral nerves. It can cause weakness, numbness, and pain, typically in the hands and feet, but it may also affect other areas and functions of the body.

diagnoses.name: Temporal Arteritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation and damage to the blood vessels that supply blood to the head, neck, upper body, and arms. It can cause headaches, scalp tenderness, jaw pain, vision problems, and sometimes life-threatening complications.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn’t produce enough thyroid hormones. Symptoms include fatigue, cold sensitivity, constipation, dry skin, and unexplained weight gain, and it can also contribute to headache disorders.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that involves visual disturbances such as scintillations and scotomas before the onset of headache, which might be accompanied by nausea and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inner ear disorder that can cause vertigo, hearing loss, tinnitus, and a feeling of fullness or congestion in the ear. Vomiting may occur during severe vertigo attacks.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). It can cause a variety of symptoms, including visual disturbances like diplopia (double vision), and, less commonly, scintillation or scotoma, as well as vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: A condition resulting from restricted blood flow to the back of the brain. Symptoms may include vertigo, dizziness, double vision (diplopia), nausea, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Depending on its location, a brain tumor can cause various neurological symptoms including scintillation, scotoma, diplopia, vertigo, and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV)
diagnoses.description: A disorder arising in the inner ear that causes short periods of vertigo when your head is moved in certain positions. It does not typically cause vomiting directly but may lead to nausea.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuronitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the vestibular nerve, leading to severe vertigo episodes that may be associated with nausea and vomiting. It commonly does not affect hearing or produce tinnitus.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A focal infection in the brain, presenting with symptoms depending on the lesion location but can include headache, vertigo, nausea, vomiting, visual symptoms like double vision or blind spots, and altered consciousness.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often referred to as a mini-stroke, a TIA can cause sudden, temporary episodes of symptoms similar to those of a stroke, including visual disturbances, vertigo, and more rarely, vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Basilar Migraine
diagnoses.description: A subtype of migraine with brainstem aura, previously known as basilar-type migraine. Symptoms include vertigo, double vision, and other disturbances possibly preceding a headache, with or without nausea and vomiting.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with symptoms such as proteinuria, due to kidney involvement, and nasal ulcers, among others.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (GPA, formerly Wegener's granulomatosis)
diagnoses.rationale: GPA is associated with nasal ulcers, kidney disease manifesting as proteinuria, and can involve peripheral nerves (mononeuritis multiplex).

diagnoses.name: Microscopic Polyangiitis (MPA)
diagnoses.rationale: This condition is known for causing renal involvement (proteinuria), as well as systemic issues such as hemolytic anemia and peripheral nerve damage.

diagnoses.name: Eosinophilic Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis (Churg-Strauss Syndrome)
diagnoses.rationale: Characterized by asthma, eosinophilia, and vasculitis involving various organs, including the skin (possibly leading to nasal ulcers), kidneys (proteinuria), and nerves (mononeuritis multiplex).

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: When severe and involving extra-articular manifestations, it can lead to vasculitis, causing symptoms like mononeuritis multiplex and skin ulcers, and renal involvement.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disorder can involve the kidneys, leading to proteinuria, and affect the peripheral nervous system. It's more known for dry eyes and mouth but can also contribute to more systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa (PAN)
diagnoses.rationale: A vasculitis that can cause kidney damage (proteinuria), skin ulcers, and peripheral neuropathy including mononeuritis multiplex.

diagnoses.name: Cryoglobulinemic Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: Associated with Hepatitis C virus infection, it primarily affects the skin, kidneys (proteinuria), and peripheral nerves.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura (HSP)
diagnoses.rationale: Though more common in children, it can present in adults with renal involvement (proteinuria), skin involvement, and rarely, other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP)
diagnoses.rationale: TTP can cause hemolytic anemia and renal involvement. Though not commonly linked to nasal ulcers or mononeuritis multiplex, it's a critical differential in cases of systemic symptoms and anemia.
